# Work Prototypes - Cursor Rules

## Project Overview
This is a Next.js-based playground for creating and sharing interactive work prototypes with colleagues. Each prototype is self-contained and focuses on demonstrating client-side behavior, animations, and UI interactions using mock data.

## Tech Stack
- **Next.js 16** (App Router, Turbopack)
- **TypeScript** (strict mode)
- **Tailwind CSS v4** (using @tailwindcss/postcss)
- **Framer Motion** (for animations)
- **shadcn/ui** (component library - add as needed)
- **React 19**

## Project Structure
```
app/
├── layout.tsx              # Root layout with minimal nav
├── page.tsx                # Home gallery listing all prototypes
├── globals.css             # Tailwind v4 + CSS variables
└── prototypes/
    └── [prototype-name]/
        ├── page.tsx        # Main prototype page (use "use client")
        ├── components/     # Prototype-specific components
        ├── lib/            # Prototype-specific utilities
        ├── mock-data.ts    # Mock data (no real APIs)
        └── reference/      # Optional: Design references, screenshots, inspiration
```

## Key Principles

### 1. Prototype Isolation
- Each prototype should be completely self-contained
- Store components, styles, and data locally within the prototype folder
- Avoid dependencies between prototypes
- Only use shared components when absolutely necessary

### 2. Client-Side Focus
- Prototypes are primarily client-side interactive demos
- Use `"use client"` directive in page.tsx
- Mock all data - no real API calls needed
- Focus on UX, animations, and interactivity

### 3. Styling Guidelines
- **Tailwind v4 syntax**: Use `@import "tailwindcss"` and `@theme` blocks
- **CSS variables**: Defined in globals.css, use `var(--color-*)` format
- **Local styles**: Prototype-specific styles should live with the prototype
- **Shared styles**: Only for global theme tokens and base styles
- Use `cn()` utility from `@/lib/utils` for className merging

### 4. Creating New Prototypes
When creating a new prototype:
1. Create folder: `app/prototypes/[kebab-case-name]/`
2. Add page.tsx with `"use client"`
3. Create mock-data.ts if needed
4. Build components in local `components/` folder
5. **IMPORTANT**: Update `app/page.tsx` to add prototype to gallery:
   ```tsx
   const prototypes: Prototype[] = [
     // ... existing
     {
       id: "new-prototype",
       title: "New Prototype",
       description: "What this demonstrates",
       tags: ["tag1", "tag2"],
     },
   ];
   ```

## Code Style

### TypeScript
- Use TypeScript for everything
- Define proper interfaces/types
- Avoid `any` - use proper types or `unknown`
- Export types from component files when reusable

### Components
- Use functional components with hooks
- Prefer named exports for components
- Use TypeScript interfaces for props
- Keep components focused and single-purpose

### Animations
- Use Framer Motion for animations
- Use consistent transition durations (0.2s, 0.3s, 0.5s)
- Prefer `motion.div` over complex animation libraries
- Consider performance - use `will-change` sparingly

### File Naming
- Components: `PascalCase.tsx` (e.g., `AnimatedCard.tsx`)
- Utilities: `kebab-case.ts` (e.g., `format-date.ts`)
- Mock data: `mock-data.ts` or `[feature]-data.ts`
- Prototypes: `kebab-case` folder names

## Common Patterns

### Responsive Design
- Mobile-first approach
- Use Tailwind breakpoints: `sm:`, `md:`, `lg:`, `xl:`, `2xl:`
- Test on different screen sizes

### Mock Data
```typescript
// Export typed mock data
export interface DataItem {
  id: string;
  // ... other fields
}

export const mockData: DataItem[] = [
  // ... data
];
```

### Animated Components
```typescript
"use client";

import { motion } from "framer-motion";

export function AnimatedComponent() {
  return (
    <motion.div
      initial={{ opacity: 0 }}
      animate={{ opacity: 1 }}
      transition={{ duration: 0.3 }}
    >
      {/* content */}
    </motion.div>
  );
}
```

## Documentation Policy

### Keep It Minimal
- ❌ **DO NOT** create separate documentation files (.md, .txt, etc.) for prototypes
- ❌ **DO NOT** create docs/ folders or extensive README updates
- ✅ **DO** make code self-documenting with clear names and types
- ✅ **DO** add brief comments for complex logic only
- ✅ **DO** use descriptive gallery descriptions (one sentence max)

### How to Document Prototypes
1. **Gallery entry** (`app/page.tsx`): One clear sentence describing what it demonstrates
2. **Page title/header**: Self-explanatory title and optional subtitle
3. **Code comments**: Only for non-obvious logic or important notes
4. **TypeScript types**: Well-named interfaces document the data structure
5. **Component names**: Clear, descriptive names make docs unnecessary

### Example (Good)
```tsx
// In app/page.tsx
{
  id: "particle-field",
  title: "Particle Field",
  description: "Interactive particle system with mouse tracking and physics",
  tags: ["animation", "canvas"],
}

// In page.tsx - title is self-documenting
<h1>Particle Field</h1>
<p>Move your mouse to interact with particles</p>
```

### README.md
- Keep focused on **setup and deployment** only
- Don't list every prototype - the gallery page does that
- Don't document features - the code should be clear
- Update only if project structure changes fundamentally

## What to Avoid
- ❌ Creating real API endpoints (use mock data)
- ❌ Adding databases or auth (client-side only)
- ❌ Complex state management (keep it simple)
- ❌ Shared state between prototypes
- ❌ Installing heavy libraries unnecessarily
- ❌ Forgetting to update the gallery page
- ❌ Using Tailwind v3 syntax (we're on v4)
- ❌ Creating separate documentation files
- ❌ Writing extensive comments for obvious code
- ❌ Updating README with prototype lists or feature docs

## Deployment Workflow

### Setup Complete
- **GitHub**: https://github.com/Hakeeb/work-prototypes
- **Vercel**: Auto-deploys on every push to main
- **Production**: Live site updates automatically

### Deploy a New Prototype (3 Steps)
1. **Build locally** - Create prototype in `app/prototypes/[name]/`
2. **Update gallery** - Add entry to `app/page.tsx`
3. **Commit & push**:
   ```bash
   git add .
   git commit -m "Add [prototype-name]"
   git push
   ```
4. **Done!** - Vercel auto-deploys in ~30 seconds

### Key Points
- Every push triggers automatic deployment
- Share URL with colleagues instantly: `/prototypes/[name]`
- No manual deploy steps needed
- Preview deployments for branches (if created)

## Adding shadcn/ui Components
```bash
npx shadcn@latest add button
npx shadcn@latest add card
```
Components will be added to `components/ui/`

## Tailwind v4 Important Notes
- Use `@import "tailwindcss"` not `@tailwind` directives
- Define theme in `@theme {}` blocks
- CSS variables use `--color-*` prefix
- PostCSS plugin is `@tailwindcss/postcss`
- Config file is minimal (just content paths)

## When Starting a New Session
1. Check `app/page.tsx` for existing prototypes
2. Look at prototype structure in `app/prototypes/`
3. Review this file for project conventions
4. Ask about the specific prototype requirements
5. Focus on clean, interactive, delightful UX
